{{c1::Nucleotides}} contain a nitrogenous base, a pentose monosaccharide ({{c1::ribose}} or {{c1::deoxyribose}}), and either one, two, or three {{c1::phosphate}}
groups.
The first step in purine synthesis is the formation of {{c1::5-Posphoribosyl-1-pyrophosphate}} ({{c1::PRPP}}) by the enzyme {{c1::PRPP synthetase}}.
{{c1::Inosine}}{{c1::monophosphate}} ({{c1::IMP}}) is used to then form AMP and GMP.
IMP is converted to adenylosuccinate by the enzyme {{c1::adenylosuccinate}} {{c1::synthetase}} requiring GTP and aspartate.
Adenine bases are added to PRPP by the enzyme {{c1::adenine}} {{c1::phosphoribosyltransferase}} ({{c1::APRT}}) with the release of pyrophosphate (PPi) to form {{c1::AMP}}.

Gout is a disease that is caused by high levels of {{c1::uric acid}}in the blood usually caused by overproduction or under excretion of {{c1::uric acid.}} Symptoms of gout can include nodular formation in soft tissue due to {{c1::MSU deposits}} (chronic tophaceous gout) and the formation of {{c1::kidney stones}} (made of uric acid). Diagnosis for gout can be made by examination of the {{c1::synovial fluid}} and revelations of the {{c1::MSU crystals.}}

The pyrimidine ring is comprised of {{c1::glutamine}} and {{c1::CO2}} that is combined by the cytoplasmic {{c1::carbamoyl}} {{c1::phosphate}} {{c1::synthetase}} {{c1::II}}. This is the regulated step in pyrimidine synthesis and is inhibited by {{c1::UTP}} and activated by high {{c1::PRPP}} levels.

Orotic aciduria can occur with result with deficiencies in either (or both) {{c1::orotate phosphoribosyltransferase}} or {{c1::OMP decarboxylase}} leading to an accumulation of orotic acid. Symptoms present as delayed growth, {{c1::megaloblastic}} anemia, and high orotic acid in the urine.  Treatment includes administration of {{c1::uridine}} to prevent the decreased pyrimidines leading to the anemia.

Clinical disorder: Gout
Defective enzyme: {{c1::PRPP synthetase}}
Nature of defect: Superactive
Characteristics: {{c1::Purine overproduction and overexcretion}}
Inheritance pattern: {{c1::X-linked}} recessive

Clinical disorder: Gout
Defective enzyme: {{c1::HGPRTase}}
Nature of defect: Partial deficiency
Characteristics: {{c1::Purine overproduction and overexcretion}}
Inheritance pattern: {{c1::X-linked}} recessive

Clinical disorder: Lesch-Nyhan Syndrome
Defective enzyme: {{c1::HGPRTase}}
Nature of defect: {{c1::Purine overproduction and overexcretion}}/ {{c1::self mutilation}}
Characteristics: Complete deficiency
Inheritance pattern: {{c1::X-linked}} recessive

Clinical disorder: {{c1::Xanthinuria}}
Defective enzyme: Xanthine oxidase
Nature of defect: Complete deficiency
Characteristics: Xanthine renal lithiasis hypouricemia
Inheritance pattern: {{c1::Autosomal}} recessive

{{c1::Nucleosides}} are classified as the nitrogenous base connected to the {{c1::pentose}} {{c1::monosaccharide}} through a N-glycosidic bond. The addition of the phosphate groups transitions the molecule from a {{c1::nucleoside}} to a {{c1::nucleotide}}.
PRPP synthetase is activated by the presence of {{c1::inorganic}} {{c1::phosphate}} and inhibited by high levels of {{c1::purine}} {{c1::ribonucleotides}}.

Activator {{c1::PRPP}} is the committed step of purine synthesis. The enzyme {{c1::glutamine}}: {{c1::phosphoribosylpyrophosphate amidotransferase}} that replaces the pyrophosphate group of PRPP with the {{c1::amide}} group of {{c1::glutamine}}. This step is inhibited by high levels of {{c1::purine nucleotides}} ({{c1::GMP}} and {{c1::AMP}}).
IMP is converted to {{c1::xanthosine}} {{c1::monophosphate}} by the enzyme IMP dehydrogenase and cofactors of {{c1::NAD+}} & {{c1::H2O}}.
Guanine and hypoxanthine are attached to PRPP is a similar manner by {{c1::hypoxanthine-guanine}} {{c1::phosphoribosyltransferase}} ({{c1::HGPRT}}) to create GMP and IMP respectively.

Lesch-Nyhan syndrome is a genetic{{c1::X-linked}}{{c1::recessive}} disorder that is caused by a deficiency in the {{c1::HGPRT}} enzyme. Patients with this disorder cannot salvage {{c1::hypoxanthine}} or {{c1::guanine}}. This results in a high amount of {{c1::uric acid}} and {{c1::hyperuricemia}},(formation of uric acid stones in the kidney and the formation of urate crystals in joints (gouty arthritis)). Symptoms include cognitive deficits, motor dysfunction, and behaviors that include {{c1::self-mutilation}} often in the form {{c1::of biting themselves (lips and fingers).}}

The treatment for gout is anti-inflammatory agents for acute attacks.  The drug allopurinol is an analog of {{c1::hypoxanthine}} and acts as an inhibitor to {{c1::xanthine}} {{c1::oxidase}}the MOA is to prevent the final steps in purine degradation and reduces the production of {{c1::uric acid}}. The {{c1::hypoxanthine}} is sent to the salvage pathway instead of being degraded.
The pyrimidine ring structure is closed by dihydroorotase and converted to {{c1::orotate}} ({{c1::orotic acid}}) by dihydroorotate dehydrogenase.

The enzyme ribonucleotide reductase is responsible for converting {{c1::ribonucleotides}} to {{c1::deoxyribonucleotides}}. Ribonucleotide reductase is activated by {{c1::ATP}} and inactivated by {{c1::dATP}}

{{c1::Kwashiorkor}} disease there is a deficiency in protein but not necessarily total calories. Individual may only have carbohydrates to eat. This decreases the synthesis of {{c1::visceral protein}} and {{c1::muscle}}. It is commonly seen in children after weaning.

Symptoms of Kwashiorkor include {{c1::stunted}} growth, skin {{c1::lesions}}, {{c1::depigmented}} hair, anorexia, {{c1::fatty}} liver, bilateral pitting edema, and {{c1::decreased}} serum albumin levels. Since the diet is mainly {{c1::carbohydrates}}, insulin can suppress {{c1::lipolysis}} and {{c1::proteolysis}}.

{{c1::Cachexia}} is a disorder that consists of loss of appetite and muscle atrophy that is NOT reversable with traditional nutritional supplement. This is commonly seen with chronic conditions like {{c1::cancer}}, {{c1::pulmonary}} disease, and {{c1::renal}} disease. It is associated with decrease tolerance for treatment and increased risk for death.

Vitamin {{c1::B9}} ({{c1::folic acid}}) deficiency leads to {{c1::macrocytic}} ({{c1::megaloblastic}}) anemia leading to the accumulation of large immature {{c1::megaloblasts}}. This form of anemia is caused by the {{c1::decrease}} in purine synthesis and {{c1::decrease}} in TMP, preventing the {{c1::megaloblasts}} from dividing and forming RBCs.

Vitamin {{c1::B 12}} ({{c1::cobalamin}}) deficiency include fatigue, weakness, dyspnea, and pale skin but may take several months to appear. Conversion of homocysteine to cysteine require both vitamin {{c1::B12}} and vitamin {{c1::B9}}, " {{c1::folate}} trap."

Mild Vitamin {{c1::B1}} ({{c1::thiamine}}) deficiency will present as gastrointestinal irregularities and a burning sensation in the feet.  A more moderate deficiency with present with peripheral {{c1::neuropathy}}, CNS {{c1::abnormalities}} and {{c1::ataxia}}.

The {{c1::D}} vitamins are a groups of sterol molecules that function similar to hormones.
Vitamin {{c1::D}} deficiency can cause {{c1::rickets}}/ {{c1::osteomalacia}}, a disease that is characteristic of demineralization of bone.
{{c1::Rickets}} (form found in children) shows formation of the collagen matrix of bone but not filled in by minerals, leading to soft malleable bones.
{{c1::Osteomalacia}} (adult form) the demineralization of existing bones increases chance of fractures.

Ethanol metabolism leads to an increase in the {{c1::NADH/NAD+}} ratio. The high {{c1::NADH/NAD+}} ratio inhibits fatty acid oxidation and the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle, resulting in accumulation of {{c1::fatty acids}} in the liver. High levels of NADH leads for the conversion of {{c1::lactate}} from {{c1::pyruvate}} and of {{c1::malate}} from {{c1::oxaloacetate}}, inhibiting gluconeogenesis. The high {{c1::NADH/NAD+}} ratio shifts oxaloacetate toward {{c1::malate}}, and {{c1::acetyl-CoA}} is directed into ketone- body synthesis.

{{c1::Marasmus}} disease is a total caloric restriction that is not limited to protein. This often occurs under the age of {{c1::one}} when {{c1::breastmilk is substituted for watered- down sources (formulas or cereals)}}.

Marasmus disease symptoms include {{c1::arrested}} growth, extreme {{c1::muscle wasting}}, depletion of f{{c1::at deposits (emaciation)}}, weakness, and anemia. There is NO {{c1::edema}} in Marasmus disease.
Fat soluble vitamins are not readily excreted and are stored in the {{c1::liver}} and {{c1::adipose tissues}}.  {{c1::Toxicity}} can occur due to build up of large quantities.

Folic acid is converted to {{c1::dihydrofolate}} ({{c1::FH2}}) and {{c1::tetrahydrofolate}} ({{c1::FH4}}) by the enzyme {{c1::dihydrofolate}} reductase, the enzyme inhibited by the drug {{c1::methotrexate}}.

Vitamin {{c1::C}} ({{c1::ascorbic acid}}) found in fruits and vegetables. Deficiencies of vitamin {{c1::C}} present as scurvy, a disease with sore and spongy gums, loose teeth, fragile blood vessels leading to hemorrhages, swollen joints, bone changes and fatigue.  {{c1::Microcytic}} anemia can present due to decreased {{c1::iron}} absorption.

{{c1::Beriberi}} is a thiamine deficiency seen in populations that eat high amounts of {{c1::polished rice}}.  Symptoms include muscle weakness/ wasting, delirium, weakness of eye muscles, memory loss, and impaired myocardial contractility.

{{c1::Wernicke-Korsakoff}} syndrome is a thiamine deficiency found in {{c1::chronic alcoholics}} due to poor diet and impaired absorption of thiamine. Symptoms include mental confusion, gait ataxia, {{c1::nystagmus}} (to-fro eye movement), {{c1::ophthalmoplegia}} (weakness of eye muscles), and hallucinations.

A deficiency in iron may cause {{c1::microcytic}}, {{c1::hypochromic}} anemia
Hereditary {{c1::hemochromatosis}} (autosomal recessive disorder) can also cause iron toxicity.
Diabetes is classified as type 1 ({{c1::insulin-dependent}} diabetes mellitus) and type 2 ({{c1::non-insulin- dependent}} diabetes mellitus).
